We recommended that Management:

a. Require the HRMA to:

i. Make a reconciliation of the leave records of all the personnel taking into consideration the errors/deficiencies noted by the Audit Team and effect the necessary adjustments and submit the updated or corrected leave cards for review and evaluation by the Audit Team;

ii. Submit the following: • Duly accomplished and verified DTRs; • Properly accomplished and approved Application for Leave filed in time; • Duly approved requests for monetization in excess of 10 days; and • Medical certificates certified by a competent and attending physician/s which shall be accompanied by clinical summary filed in time;

iii. Conduct monthly posting of earned vacation leave and sick leave and establish a protocol for the immediate posting of monetization of leave credits, approved application for leave and undertime to prevent delays and potential overstatement of leave credit balances; and

b. Instruct all personnel to observe all rules and regulations on leave to ensure that the same deficiencies will not be incurred by the Municipality in the future.

We recommended that Management:

a. Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to assign capable personnel within the Treasury Office who will be in-charge of the issuance of Notice of Delinquency and the monitoring of the delinquent taxpayers;

b. Intensify the tax campaign, through the office of the Municipal Treasurer by sending treasury personnel to barangays, especially during barangay assemblies, for tax information drive to encourage more taxpayers to pay their taxes on time;

c. Require the Municipal Treasurer to explore other effective strategies to improve tax collection rates, such as enhancing information dissemination efforts, streamlining payment processes, and implementing incentives or penalties to encourage timely tax payments;

d. Utilize all available remedies provided by law, such as administrative and judicial actions, to collect delinquent real property taxes; and

e. Implement levy on real property and conduct public auctions if necessary to satisfy tax delinquencies.

We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendations that Management:

a. Create an organizational structure which will outline the flow of activities and define the roles and responsibilities of the personnel assigned in the waterworks system consistent with Resolution No. 079-2001 and Ordinance No. 2001-02 dated March 5, 2001;

b. Require the designated Chief of Section, with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer, MPDC, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant, to formulate written policies and procedures on the operation of the waterworks system which will serve as a guide to efficient and effective management and to achieve the goal of providing potable water to households and maximize the use of the resources to generate additional income to the Municipality;

c. Review the rates per cubic meter of water consumption as provided in Ordinance No. 2001-002 dated March 5, 2001 to determine its reasonableness as compared with the existing rates of nearby water districts or water facilities and with the personal services and maintenance and operating expenses incurred in the operation of the waterworks system which shall serve as basis in implementing rate increase and in the improvement of delivery of services; and

d. Implement internal controls to prevent financial loss and ensure efficiency in operations such as issuance of water bills with control numbers to enhance accountability and control and alignment of expenses with income to prevent financial losses and guarantee sustainability.

We recommended that Management:

a. Require the MSWMB to comply immediately with the requirements of the DENR-EMB in the issuance of NTP for the operation of the Sanitary Landfill;

b. Instruct the MPDC to include the procurement of the necessary equipment and facilities especially those that are used in treatment of spreading and compacting solid wastes and grading of the covered surfaces as priority development projects to minimize loose layers and maximize the space in the landfill;

c. Direct the MSWMB to comply with the minimum criteria in the establishment and operation of Sanitary Landfill to improve efficiency in its operation and ensure the protection of personnel, public health and environment; and

d. Require the HRMA to assign qualified personnel occupying permanent position in the operations of the Sanitary Landfill who shall ensure proper handling of solid wastes.

We recommended that Management:

a.	Require the OIC Municipal Budget Officer to monitor properly the expenditures and obligations incurred by the LGU before certifying the availability of appropriation in the Obligation Request to avoid the incurrence of negative balance of appropriations;

b.	Direct the OIC Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that the funds received from the Bayanihan Grant are utilized for COVID-19 related PPAs and to review carefully and determine the conformity of the PPAs with the provisions of the DBM Circular before certifying the availability of allotment in the Bayanihan Grant;

c.	Require the Chairman of the BAC, with the assistance of the BAC Secretariat, to post all NOA, contract, or purchase order in the website of the LGU, if any, or any conspicuous place in the premises of the Procuring Entity and GPPB online portal for Emergency Procurement under the Bayanihan Act for transparency purposes and to require the submission of the mandatory documentary requirements from the suppliers, distributors, manufacturers or contractors concerned; and

d.	Require the Municipal Accountant, with the assistance of the MSWDO and MHO, to submit the list of affected families and proof of receipt of distribution of relief goods, medicines and vitamins and use of testing kits and other supporting documents.

We recommended that Management:

a.    Require the BAC, with the assistance of the BAC Secretariat and TWG, to verify the accuracy of the NFCC, list of contractor’s equipment and other eligibility requirements, validate the availability and operating condition of the equipment and check the performance of the bidder in its on-going or completed projects in order to ensure that government contracts are awarded to qualified bidders;

b.    Instruct the BAC to require the bidders to use the prescribed forms in the bidding documents and emphasize the possibility of non-acceptance of bid for non-compliance, to indicate their initial in every page of the original copies of the bid received and opened and to cause the posting of the NOA, Contract and NTP in the agency website;

c.    Direct the Municipal Engineer to require the contractor to submit the written consent of bondsmen for extension of contract time and certification from the DTI on the delays of delivery or shortage of construction materials, and to determine the reasonable number of days of time extension based on PAGASA weather report and impose liquidated damages on the delays in accordance with Section 8.1, Annex “E” of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and


d.    Require the Municipal Accountant, with the assistance of the BAC Secretariat, to submit the lacking documents for further evaluation of the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:

a.    Instruct the Municipal Engineer to require the contractor to undertake the immediate repair of the cracks and scaling in the PCCP to avoid penetration of the water and prevent further deterioration that may affect the efficiency and effectiveness of the project;




b.    Require the BAC, with the assistance of the Technical Working Group, to verify the accuracy of the list of equipment and other eligibility requirements submitted by the bidders and check the performance of the bidder in its on-going or completed projects in order to ensure that government contracts are awarded to qualified bidders, and the BAC Secretariat to post the NOA, Contract and NTP in the agency website;




c.    Require the BAC to affix their initials in every page of the original copies of the bid received and opened; and 



d.    Instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the supporting documents for further evaluation of the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:    

a.	Direct the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board (MSWMB) to implement the mandatory segregation of solid waste and stop the practice of transporting wastes to the controlled dumpsite;




b.	Require the MSWMB to facilitate the completion of the WACS in order to secure the approval of the 10-year solid waste management plan and its immediate implementation and to comply immediately with the requirements of the DENR EMB in the issuance of NTP for the operation of the Sanitary Landfill;




c.	Instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to include the completion of the concreting of road going to the Sanitary Landfill and procurement of the necessary equipment to be funded by the Municipal Development Fund and to require the HRMA to provide the personnel necessary for its operation; and


d.	Impose collection of solid waste management fees in amounts sufficient to pay the costs of preparing, adopting and implementing a solid waste management plan and charge fines and penalties against persons committing the prohibited acts provided in Section 48 of RA No. 9003 through Sanggunian Bayan Ordinance.

We recommended that Management:

a.	Require the BAC, with the assistance of the TWG, to verify the accuracy of the NFCC and other eligibility requirements submitted by the bidders and to verify, validate and ascertain the on-going or completed projects of the bidder as to incurrence of delays, failure of delivery or unsatisfactory performance of obligations as well as the inspection and testing of the goods/products and indicate the results thereof in the Post-Qualification Report in order to ensure that government contracts are awarded to qualified bidders;

b.	Instruct the BAC, with the assistance of the BAC Secretariat, to invite observers in the procurement activities consistent with the requirements of Section 13 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, post the NOA, Contract and NTP in the agency website and require the bidders to use the prescribed forms in the bidding documents and emphasize the possibility of non-acceptance of bid for non-compliance to promote transparency and accountability in procurement transactions;

c.	Require the BAC to affix their initials in every page of the original copies of the bid received and opened; and 


d.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents for further evaluation of the Audit Team and to impose liquidated damages amounting to ₱87,945.00 to the Supplier due to incurrence of 55 calendar days of delay in the delivery of the vehicle purchased.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the BAC to ensure that the issuance of NOA is within the stipulated period;
Require the BAC to affix their initials in every page of the original copies of the bid received and opened;
Require the BAC Secretariat to clearly address the invitations sent to the duly recognized private group;
Instruct the BAC to ensure that projects indicated in the Statement of all Ongoing Government and Private Contracts awarded but not yet completed are duly supported with NTP, Contract and Certificate of Accomplishment;
Require the BAC Secretariat to ensure that Minutes of Pre-Bid Conference and Notification letters addressed to the contractors are duly signed;
Instruct the BAC to ensure that projects indicated in the SLCC are duly supported with Certificate of Final Acceptance issued by the project owner or a final rating of at least Satisfactory in the CPES;
Require the BAC Secretary to ensure that Notification letters addressed to the contractors are duly signed; and
Require the BAC and Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents to support claims for review of the Audit Team and ensure that documents are properly signed and dated.

